The Telegraph - Calcutta
 Saturday, October 26, 2002 				Metro Recommends
				 																The Album				 																																	(Kabir Suman)				 																																	lAs the title suggests, most of the 10 numbers draw from religion. Dilshad, Shikarir Khoje and the title song carry Sumans trademark nuances. For some soul-stirring effect, Ekta Thalaye and Ayan Rashid are the other numbers to watch out for				 																The Show				 																																	(October 26, Saturday Club Phoenix, 7.30 pm)				 																																	lA fashion and jewellery extravaganza, accompanied by a performance by singer Tritha, presented by the Calcutta Round Table 34, (Park Street). All proceeds go in aid of underprivileged children. Entry by invitation only				 																Exhibition				 																																	(October 26 to 30, Ice Skating Rink, 11 am to 8 pm)				 																																	lAn exhibition-cum-sale of seasonal items, including diyas, candles, jewellery, garments, furniture, home appliances and other goods, by leading brands				 																The Book				 																																	(Esther David)				 																																	lA heart-warming account of the lives and loves of a Jewish family in India. Poignant yet intriguing, the author chronicles the joys and sorrows of her family, following their adventures spanning generations, in an attempt to find her own roots
